                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d698">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">102.1/10–2844: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-28T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >October 28, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1395. For Friedman from Under Secretary Bell. Reference your no. 1629, September
                    30, 1944.</p>
                <pb facs="0960" n="946" xml:id="pg_946"/>
                <p>Treasury understands that United States Government personnel paid in United
                    States currency has been selling currency in open market and then using yuan to
                    purchase United States dollar drafts from United Clearing Board, resulting in
                    exchange profit for such personnel.</p>
                <p>The Treasury has received a copy of circular no. 49, dated July 18, 1944,
                    addressed by Ambassador Gauss to American diplomatic and consular officers in
                    China on the subject of exchange transactions for profit. The Treasury is in
                    agreement with the policy incorporated in such circular, and you are instructed
                    to advise Evans and any other Treasury personnel arriving in China that the
                    Treasury expects them to be governed accordingly. [Bell.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
